ritics, femininity—a newly emerging and primarily bourgeois ideal—linked women and music under the valorized signs of refinement, sensibility, virtue, patriotism, luxury, and, above all, beauty. This moment in musical history was eclipsed in the first decades of the nineteenth century, and ultimately erased from the music-historical record, by now familiar developments: the formation of musical canons, a musical history based on technical progress, the idea of masterworks, authorial autonomy, the musical sublime, and aggressively essentializing ideas about the relationship between sex, gender and art. In Sovereign Feminine, Matthew Head restores this earlier musical history and explores the role that women played in the development of classical music.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGender identity in music. 0aMusicxSocial aspectszGermanyxHistoryy18th century. 0aMusiczGermanyy18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aWomen musicianszGermanyxHistoryy18th century. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh  a18th century.  a19th century.  aart.  aauthorial autonomy.  abeauty.  abourgeois ideal.  aclassical music.  aclassical.  acommercial culture.  aengaging.  afemale composers.  afemale excellence.  afemale musicians.  afemininity.  afeminocentric values.  afine arts.  agender studies.  agerman states.  aluxury.  amasterworks.  amusic.  amusical canons.  amusical composers.  amusical history.  amusical performers.  amusical.  apatriotism.  aperforming arts.  arefinement.  asensibility.  asex.  asocial issues.  avirtue.  awomens history.  awomens issues.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027384940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/97805209